                        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                        
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mrow>
                          <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                          <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                          <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>Q</m:mi>
                        <m:mrow>
                          <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                          <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                          <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                        </m:mrow>
                        
                        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                        
                        <m:mover accent="true">
                          <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                          <m:mo>˜</m:mo>
                        </m:mover>
                        <m:mrow>
                          <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                          <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                          <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                      </m:mrow>
                    </m:mtd>
                  </m:mtr>
                </m:mtable>
              </m:math>
            </equation>
            Thus, the reconstructed output is corrupted only by the quantization error.
            Another significant advantage to placing the quantizer inside the
prediction loop is realized if the predictor made self-adaptive
(in the same spirit as the adaptive quantizers we studied).
As illustrated in <link target-id="adaptive"/>, adaptation of the prediction
coefficients can take place simulateously at the encoder and
decoder with no transmission of side-information (e.g. <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="bold">h</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math>)!
This is a consequence of the fact that both algorithms have access
to identical signals.
